In Java and many other programming languages, you can't rename a function or variable directly. However, there are ways to achieve this functionality using method overloading (also known as "method chaining") in combination with the concept of methods within classes that return instances themselves for further use cases like renaming functions:

```java 
public class Try {  
    void abc() {}     // original function/variable name 'abc' is here.

    public Object ref(){      // new method to chain calls, returns the instance itself (Object type) so you can use it for further operations like bitch().ref(); 
        this.bitch();         // calling abc() in a way that makes sense within its context  
                              // e.g., if 'abc' was called from another method and we want to call the same function again, then do so here: ref(), not just refer it as bitch(). 
        return this;          // returns instance itself (Object type) for further use cases like chaining calls or calling methods on top of current object.  
    }                         

    public void bitch(){       // new method to rename 'abc' into another name, e.g., renaming it as you want: 
        abc();                // original function/variable call here (calling the same functionality)     
                              // if this was called from a different context or not in its current scope then do so like bitch().bitch()  
    }                         
}                           
```                                                      
In your example, you can use `ref` method to chain calls and rename function as follows: 
- Calling the original 'abc' (renamed into a new name) in its context. e.g., if it was called from another class or other methods then do so like bitch().bitch();  
Or, you can call this method again to start chain of calls and rename function as follows:  ref(), not just refer the resultant object for further use cases such calling same functionality in next step. e.g., if 'abc' was called from another class or other methods then do so like bitch().ref();

